text: Antibacterial Pentacyclic Polyketides from a Soil-Derived Streptomyces ⊥ Jie Yuan, and Sheng-Xiong Huang* ABSTRACT: Nine new pentacyclic polyketides, fasamycins G−K (1−5) and formicamycins N−Q (6−9), along with 10 known analogues (10−19), were isolated from a rhizospheric soil-derived structures and absolute Streptomyces conﬁgurations were elucidated by interpretation of NMR and HRMS data and comparisons of CD data. The compounds were active against methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA), Staphylococcus aureus, Bacillus subtilis, and Escherichia coli strains, with MIC values ranging from 0.20 to 50.00 μg/mL. M ethicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) has been a major cause of nosocomial infections since the 1960s.1,2 It can lead to various human and animal diseases, including skin infections, abscesses, pneumonia, mastitis, osteomyelitis, septicemia, and acute endocarditis.3,4 Vancomy- cin was considered as the ﬁrst-line drug to treat serious MRSA infections, but many clinical isolates of vancomycin-resistant MRSA have been found worldwide.5,6 Therefore, the exploration of novel and more eﬃcient antibacterial agents against MRSA is urgently needed. Fasamycins and formica- mycins are two subtypes of structurally related pentacyclic polyketides with signiﬁcant antibacterial activity against methicillin-resistant S. aureus and vancomycin-resistant Enter- faecalis (VRE),7−14 through inhibiting poly(ADP- ococcus ribose) polymerase-1 (PARP-1).15 The synthesis14,16,17 and biosynthesis7,18 of fasamycins and formicamycins were recently reported.

As part of our continuing search for new bioactive secondary metabolites from Streptomyces isolated from rhizospheric soil,19,20 we investigated the chemical constituents of Streptomyces sp. KIB-1414, a strain from the rhizospheric soil of Polyalthia cerasoides, which showed antimicrobial activities against pathogenic bacteria stains including S. aureus ATCC 6538, Bacillus subtilis ATCC 6633, and Escherichia coli ATCC 8099. Nine new pentacyclic polyketides (Figure 1), fasamycins G−K (1−5) and formicamycins N−Q (6−9), together the known fasamycin C (10),7 fasamycin E (11),7 7-(2,4- dimethoxy-6-methylphenyl)-2,4,6-trihydroxy-9-methoxy- 12,12-dimethyltetracen-5(12H)-one (12),14 naphthacemycin B4 (13),8 formicamycin A (14),7 formicamycin B (15),7 formicamycin C (16),7 formicamycin E (17),7 formicamycin F (18),7 and formicamycin G (19),7 were isolated (Figure S1, Cite This: https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acs.jnatprod.0c00161 © XXXX American Chemical Society and American Society of Pharmacognosy Jian-Ping Huang, Mingming Yu, Jun Tang, Yijun Yan, Jing Yang,* Figure 1. Chemical structures of compounds 1−9. Supporting Information). Herein, we report details of the isolation, structure elucidation, and antibacterial activities of these new pentacyclic polyketides. Formicamycin N (6) was isolated as a faint yellow powder. The HRESIMS data of 6 indicated a molecular formula of C29H27ClO8, corresponding to 16 degrees of unsaturation. The NMR data of 6 and formicamycin A (14)7 were similar (Tables 1 and 2) except that one methoxy group (δ H 3.81, δ C 54.3) in 14 was absent in 6. Further HMBC experimentation to conﬁrm the formicamycin (Figure 2) was carried out skeleton and the positions of methoxyls. Key HMBC correlations of H3-28/C-23 and H3-29/C-3 in 6 showed the two methoxy groups to be at C-23 and C-3, respectively. As was the case of formicamycin B (15),7 the NOESY spectrum of 6 revealed the same key NOE correlations of H-16/H3-26, H- 16/H3-27, H-19/H3-26, H-19/H3-27, H-20a/H3-26, H-20b/ H3-26, and H-20a/H-19 (Figure 4). Therefore, as with formicamy- cin B (15),7 a stereochemistry of (10R, 19R) was assigned to 6 based on a combination of NOESY NMR and experimental CD data. However, in formicamycin B (15) remained unsolved. As reported,7 neither the observed weak NOE correlation between H-24 and H3-25 nor the calculated ECDs of relevant P,M-conﬁgurations of the axial chirality can distinguish two possible atropisomers. In view of the shared biosynthesis pathway for fasamycins and formicamycins, we tentatively determined that the axial −C7 in formicamycin N (6) was the same (P- chirality at C6 conﬁguration) as that of fasamycins G−K (1−5). Formicamycin O (7) has the same molecular formula, formicamycin N (6) according to its C29H27ClO8, as HRESIMS data. A coupling interaction between H-22 (δ H 6.49, d, 3.0) in the 1H−1H COSY 6.80, d, 2.4) and H-24 (δ spectrum of 7 (Figure S48, Supporting Information) suggested the chlorination was not at C-22 in 7 like that of that formicamycin N (6). Instead, no aromatic protons coupled with H-4 (δ H 6.50, s) in the 1H−1H COSY spectrum of 7, and the carbon at C-2 (δ C 113.8) is nonprotonated rather than oleﬁnic as in 6, so the chlorine atom should be at C-2. This was further supported by HMBC data.

The molecular formula of formicamycin P (8) was indicated as C28H25ClO8 from its HRESIMS data, with one carbon atom and two hydrogen atoms less than that of formicamycin N (6). An aromatic methoxyl (δ H3.61, δ C 56.1) was indicated by the 1D NMR data of 8 (Tables 1 and 2), and further HMBC correlation from H3-29 (δ C 158.2) showed a methoxyl at C-3 (Figure S54, Supporting Information). Thus, the axial chirality at C6 the methoxyl in formicamycin N (6) at C-23 was replaced by a hydroxy in formicamycin P (8). The quasi-molecular ion peak in the HRESIMS spectrum at m/z 585.1088 [M − H]− provided the molecular formula C30H28Cl2O8 for formicamycin Q (9). The NMR data of 9 (Tables 1 and 2) and formicamycin B (15)7 were similar, except for an additional methoxyl (δ H 3.98, δ C 56.4) and a downﬁeld shifted (∼4 ppm) carbon signal at δ C 155.2 (C-5). An HMBC correlation from the methoxyl (δ H 3.98) to C-5 (δ C 155.2) indicated the additional methoxy group is attached to C-5. Finally, the stereochemistries at C-10 and C-19 were both assigned to be R as in formicamycin N (6) based on their − respective CD spectra (Figure 3B). The axial chiralities at C6 C7 in formicamycins O−Q (7−9) were tentatively assigned to be P as in 6.

Compounds 1−19 were evaluated for their antibacterial activities,21 and their minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) values are listed in Table 3. All compounds showed antibacterial activities against methicillin-resistant S. aureus (MRSA), S. aureus, B. subtilis, and E. coli with MIC values ranging from 0.20 to 50.00 μg/mL. Compounds 4, 11, 12, 14, 15, and 16 exhibited strong antibacterial activity against MRSA with an MIC value of 1.56 μg/mL, equal to that of vancomycin. Notably, the antibacterial activity of 19 against MRSA was better than that of vancomycin with an MIC value of 0.20 μg/mL. Compound 6 showed stronger antibacterial activities against all the tested bacterial strains than 8, which might result from the absence of methoxy modiﬁcation at C-23 in 8. Compared with formicamycin Q (9), compounds 17 and 18 also showed more potent antibacterial activity. It is possible that the chlorination modiﬁcation at C-14 or C-16 in ring E played an important role in determining their antibacterial activities. Formicamycin G (19), with a meta-chlorinated ring, showed the most potent antibacterial activities against all tested strains.

Strain Isolation and Cultivation. Strain Streptomyces sp. KIB- 1414 was isolated from the rhizosphere soil of Polyalthia cerasoides, which was collected in Yuxi, Yunnan Province, China, in 2015. It was identiﬁed as Streptomyces sp. by a 16S rRNA gene sequence (GenBank No. MN065804) showing 99.1% identity to that of strain Streptomyces sclerogranulatus JT18 (GenBank No. MG669348.1).

This strain was cultured on MS agar plates (2.0% soybean powder, 2.0% mannitol, and 2.0% agar, pH 7.2) for 5 days at 30 °C. The spores were inoculated into 250 mL baﬄed Erlenmeyer ﬂasks containing 50 mL of liquid TSB medium (tryptone soy broth, 30 g/L) and shaken on a rotary shaker (200 rpm) at 30 °C for 2 days. The fermentation scale for strain Streptomyces sp. KIB-1414 was 20 L in total. Extraction and Isolation. The culture was centrifuged at 4000 rpm at 4 °C for 15 min. The supernatant was extracted three times with equal volumes of EtOAc. The mycelia was soaked with acetone and then concentrated under reduced pressure to yield the aqueous concentrate, which was further extracted with equivalent EtOAc three times. Both EtOAc extracts were ultimately combined to get the crude extract due to their similar HPLC metabolite proﬁles.

The extract (8.6 g) was then subjected to silica gel CC eluting with petroleum ether−EtOAc (1:0, 10:1, 5:1, 3:1, 1:1, and 1:0, v/v) and EtOAc−CH3OH (1:1, v/v) to give seven fractions (A−G). Antimicrobial Assay. The antimicrobial activities of compounds 1−19 were investigated in 96-well plates using a modiﬁed broth microdilution method.21 Four bacteria are used [methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (shhs A1), Staphylococcus aureus (ATCC 6538), Bacillus subtilis (ATCC 6633), and Escherichia coli (ATCC 8099)]. A 195 μL amount of LB medium (1.0% tryptone, 0.5% yeast extract, 1.0% NaCl, pH 7.4) was dispensed in each well of column 1, while columns 2−12 contained 100 μL of LB medium only. Each tested compound (5 μL, dissolved in DMSO at a concentration of 4 mg/ mL), positive controls kanamycin (5 μL, dissolved in water at a concentration of 4 mg/mL) and vancomycin (5 μL, dissolved in water at a concentration of 4 mg/mL), and negative control DMSO (5 μL) were dispensed in wells of column 1, respectively. Then the mixture from columns 1−10 was transferred and mixed, yielding 100 μL of 2- fold serial dilutions per well. Each of the tested bacterial strains was cultured in LB medium on a rotatory (200 rpm) at 37 °C for 12 h and added to columns 1−11, resulting in approximately 5 × 105 CFU/mL per well. Final tested sample concentrations were 50, 25, 12.5, 6.25, 3.125, 1.5625, 0.7813, 0.3906, 0.1953, and 0.0977 μg/mL. Column 12 contained 100 μL of LB medium (as a control to monitor sterility).22 The microplates were further incubated at 37 °C for 16 h. The minimum inhibitory concentration was determined as the lowest concentration inhibiting visible growth of bacteria. All the experi- ments were carried out in triplicate.
